releases/0/tender/title: Preparedness of recent medical graduates to meet anticipated healthcare needs
releases/0/tender/description:
This research aims to understand to what extent recent graduates (i.e. doctors in foundation training) are prepared to meet specific anticipated healthcare needs. The proposed research approach is to explore whether graduate doctors have the skills, capabilities and attributes to meet the needs identified within three focus themes:
The changing patient-doctor relationship
The doctor in a multi-disciplinary team
Complex clinical decision making
The findings of this research will support our engagement with the development of the NHS People Plan and other workforce planning, as well as informing any further review/updating of our regulation of the undergraduate medical education or foundation programme.

releases/0/tender/title: Drivers of international migration of doctors to and from the United Kingdom
releases/0/tender/description:
The aim of the research is to use available evidence to a) understand the flow of doctors to and from the UK; and b) describe the migration push and pull factors. The research should explore the complex range of factors driving international migration of doctors, comparing the situation in the UK with other high-income countries.
It is hoped that as well as summarising knowledge on this topic, the research will put the GMC in a stronger position to anticipate and where necessary respond to trends and factors that are impacting the migration of doctors. It is hoped that the research will have direct implications for GMC operational planning as well as contributing to the wider debate on workforce planning.

releases/0/tender/title: NHS Calderdale CCG: Community Dermatology Service (AQP)
releases/0/tender/description:
NHS Calderdale Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) is seeking to procure the provision of a community dermatology service for the population of Calderdale, offering a 3 year contract with the option to extend for up to a further 1 year and a break clause applicable after year 2. The procurement will be an Any Qualified Provider (AQP) process. 

This will operate within the wider context of dermatology service provision across the West Yorkshire and Harrogate Health and Care Partnership.

The Calderdale Community Dermatology Service is for people whose mild to moderate skin condition cannot be managed by a generalist/GP, and who need to access intermediate care, provided by a multi-disciplinary team. 

The purpose of the Service is to provide comprehensive and equitable dermatology treatment and care closer to home, in the community, potentially aligned to Calderdale Primary Care Networks.  The Service will provide timely and appropriate access to advice, diagnosis, treatment and follow up that meets patients' physical and psychological needs. It will contribute to the delivery of an efficient local Dermatology health system for people registered with a Calderdale General Practice.  The Service will operate through a fully integrated, accessible model of care for people, ensuring the specialist elements of the service are delivered within a high quality and cost effective framework through the effective and sustainable use of resources, and streamlined referral and management processes.

The Service will be provided by a consultant-led multidisciplinary team which offers:
•	Clinical triage assessment and treatment
•	Advice, diagnosis, care and treatment in line with national standards
•	Shared decision making, based on the NHS comprehensive model of personalised care
•	Self-management as a core element of agreed care plans
•	Cohesive and seamless pathways based on patient need
•	Support for the delivery of high quality cancer services in line with national guidance
•	Technology that facilitates the delivery of high quality patient outcomes (where it is clinically appropriate to do so), such as teledermatology and virtual clinics

Service Providers are encouraged to demonstrate an innovative and flexible approach to the delivery of a community dermatology service that can meet the needs of people and communities in Calderdale now, and in the future, within the wider context of dermatology service provision across the West Yorkshire and Harrogate Health and Care Partnership.

Service Providers will need to collaborate and communicate with other Providers and partners delivering the Calderdale, and West Yorkshire and Harrogate, Dermatology health system.

releases/0/tender/title: A Request for the Provision of Fire Risk Assessment Services across Peterborough City Council Premises
releases/0/tender/description:
Peterborough City Council wishes to appoint a suitably experienced and qualified Supplier, for a period of 36 months commencing April 2020, to fulfil the role of the 'Competent Person' in the production of Fire Risk Assessments (FRA). 
This includes the following:

a)	Complete a FRA for each premises.
b)	Undertake interim FRA as and when/if building changes have been made
c)	Establish a three year cycle to undertaking the FRA in line with the attached 'Premise List'.
d)	FRA must be completed within the agreed timescale. 
e)	Cover various types of premises ranging from offices, schools, blocks of flats, leisure facilities, libraries, pavilions, community centres. 
f)	Provide an Action Plan (AP) of recommendations identified within the FRA.

The FRA is required to systematically evaluate the factors that determine a possible hazard from fire within the premises and to assist with the protection from fire. It may also include the assessment of the property issues and to some extent, how to retain business continuity i.e. advising on the potential threats to the business due to outcomes of the assessment and how to mitigate risks to ensure business as usual if a site were to be affected by fire.

releases/0/tender/title: Community Paediatric Nutrition Prescribing Support Dietitian (PSD) Service for Mid Essex Clinical Commissioning Group
releases/0/tender/description:
This is a Contract Award Notice to communicate NHS Mid Essex Clinical Commissioning Group's recent contract award to Oviva UK Limited for the provision of technology-enabled, community paediatric nutrition prescribing support dietitian (PSD) service for a period of 12 months.
The CCG commissioned a pilot technology-enabled, community paediatric nutrition prescribing support dietitian (PSD) service from Oviva UK Limited in May 2018, following a procurement process. This provider also delivers a paediatric home enteral feed dietetic service in Mid Essex and cow's milk allergy services for the South East Essex CCGs. 
The CCG is currently preparing for an STP merger with the South Essex Clinical Commissioning Groups with the aim of being a single organisation by April 2021. As such, the CCG has made the decision that working with their existing provider to continue to develop the service by extending the pilot will be the best solution to provide a technology-enabled, community paediatric nutrition prescribing support dietitian (PSD) service for Mid Essex until the new organisation is in a position to make strategic commissioning decisions for future provision of community dietetics for the STP.
The CCG is publishing this Contract Award Notice in the Contracts Finder in accordance with the Public Contracts Regulations 2015 for spend above £25,000.The Services in scope of this Contract Award Notice fall within 'social and other specific services' within the Public Contracts Regulations 2015 (the Regulations) but the total contract value of £70,000 does not exceed the current threshold of £663,540.

The Authority has secured funding from the European Regional Development Fund (ERDF) for the Killingworth Site Sustainable Retrofit project. This project is a combination of refurbishment and replacement of the existing office accommodation, workshop, welfare and other facilities on the site ensuring it 'future proofs' its operations, with energy efficiency and functionality as the key principles using a range of energy efficient systems, alongside energy generation and energy storage/distribution solutions to support a move to an electronic powered operational fleet.

releases/0/tender/title: A303 Sparkford to Ilchester Dualling Ecology
releases/0/tender/description:
NOTIFICATION OF SUBCONTRACT PACKAGE
A303 Sparkford to Ilchester
Galliford Try, as the South West Regional Delivery Partner are delivering the A303 Sparkford to Ilchester dualling project in the county of Somerset on behalf of Highways England. The project involves the design and construction of 5.6km of new dual lane all-purpose carriageway, connecting the existing dual carriageway at the Sparkford and Podimore Bypasses, therefore creating a continuous dual carriageway between Mere and the Podimore Roundabout.
The project is currently awaiting the approval of the Development Consent Order from the Secretary of State for Transport and this is expected to be given in early Spring 2020. Subject to receiving approval, the project is forecast to commence on site in late summer 2020 and will take around 2 years to complete.  
Package: ECOLOGY 	
Outline Scope of Works   
The ecology works are to be provided in accordance with the scope documents contained and referred to within this enquiry document. The majority of the new A303 dual carriageway sits to the north of the existing A303 however the new and existing carriageways cross at approx. ch3300 & ch3750.  
Programme
It is currently anticipated that the ecology works will commence in autumn 2021.
Timings
Deadline for Notifications of Interest	17:30hrs 13th April 2020
Deadline for tender submission  	17:30hrs 20th April 2020

If this package is of interest to your company please contact the Managing QS [Adrian Paddock] by e-mail on adrian.paddock@gallifordtry.co.uk, by the above deadline for notifications of interest and a link to the subcontract enquiry documentation can be issued.

Galliford Try, as the South West Regional Delivery Partner are delivering the A303 Sparkford to Ilchester dualling project in the county of Somerset on behalf of Highways England. The project involves the design and construction of 5.6km of new dual lane all-purpose carriageway, connecting the existing dual carriageway at the Sparkford and Podimore Bypasses, therefore creating a continuous dual carriageway between Mere and the Podimore Roundabout.
The project is currently awaiting the approval of the Development Consent Order from the Secretary of State for Transport and this is expected to be given in early Spring 2020. Subject to receiving approval, the project is forecast to commence on site in late summer 2020 and will take around 2 years to complete.  
Package: STEEL BRIDGE BEAM SUPPLY & INSTALL	
Outline Scope of Works   
The steel bridge beam scope includes fabricate, delivery and erection [including all necessary craneage and lifting] of the steel beams to Steart Hill bridge all in accordance with the scope documents contained and referred to within this enquiry document. The majority of the new A303 dual carriageway sits to the north of the existing A303 however the new and existing carriageways cross at approx. ch3300 & ch3750.  
Programme
It is currently anticipated that the steel bridge beam works will commence in late 2021 /early 2022.
Timings
Deadline for Notifications of Interest	17:30hrs 11th April 2020
Deadline for tender submission  	17:30hrs 16th April 2020

If this package is of interest to your company please contact the Managing QS [Adrian Paddock] by e-mail on adrian.paddock@gallifordtry.co.uk, by the above deadline for notifications of interest and a link to the subcontract enquiry documentation can be issued.

The City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council (The Council) operates a fleet of approximately 500 road going vehicles comprising of cars, small vans, mini buses, tippers, road sweepers, refuse collection vehicles. 

The Council is seeking a to appoint one or more (to a maximum of four) Contractor(s)(s) to provide a repair service for :

LOT 1 - Vehicles up to and including 5,000kg GVW
LOT 2 - Heavy vehicles over 5,000kg and up to 44,000kg GVW.

Contractors must be aware that LOT 1 will include Long Wheel Base vans and minibuses that can be approx. 3 mtrs high and 7mtrs long. Contractors must have sufficient space (i.e. spray booth size) to cater for this size.

The annual expenditure for this service is estimated to be circa £80,000 based on previous expenditure. This value should be only used to indicate possible levels of business for this contract. The Council cannot guarantee any particular volume of business to any Contractor(s).

The contract will be awarded initially for a three year period; the Council reserves the right to extend for a further 1 year period.  The extension is subject to quality of service and price remaining acceptable to the Council.  The maximum contract period is 4 years.

releases/0/tender/title: Growth Service for Businesses in Cambridgeshire & Peterborough
releases/0/tender/description:
This Procurement is to appoint an Organisation to administer - A capital Growth Investment Fund of grants and equity investments, as well as an Innovation & Relocation Grant 

The contract is to appoint a single company or prime contractor/ consortia type arrangement to support the CPCA in delivering the Local Industrial Strategy by way of four specific areas of growth.  

These include:
An Inclusive Growth Service, 
to engage our highest potential growth firms to better support them to accelerate their growth, increase their capacity and capability for growth, sustain their period within growth, or all three. 

An Inward Investment Service, 
to extend our reach into key global markets, to engage and persuade overseas firms to locate into our economy or invest in our strategic projects to increase our employment space, develop our transport infrastructure or establish a new university.

A Skills Service, 
to provide an effective brokerage between young talent and those retraining or progressing in a career, our employers and our skills providers, to improve the supply of skills to enable growth. 

A Capital Growth or Innovation & Re-Location Grant 
to co-invest with small firms in the cost of contracting experts to help either through £50k grants or equity investments;
 - to provide access to R&D funding from UK and EU agencies for new product growth and increased productivity
 - to provide access to fast-track planning, partners and investment for new build employment space  

These service will be delivered in each of our three sub-economies in a tailored manner to better spread growth more evenly across our total economy.This revised notice is to highlight a number of significant changes. 

CHANGES SINCE THE PREVIOUS NOTICE
The CPCA is procuring this contract on behalf of the Cambridgeshire and Peterborough Business Growth Company (CPBGC) who a wholly own subsidiary of the CPCA, established for the sole purpose of delivering this contract.  The CPCA will act as agent for the CPBGC and will provide the support services for both the procurement and delivery of the resultant contract.

In addition, the Procurement has been extended in time to address the current commercial challenges surrounding the COVID-19 Pandemic.

Finally, the specification has been extended to include the flexibility to respond to both the current economic situation and any future, unknown business challenges the local businesses may face in the future.

releases/0/tender/title: Cambridge City Council - Hybrid Mailing and Printing for Cambrdge City and Huntingdonshire District Councils
releases/0/tender/description:
The Councils' (Cambridge City and Huntingdonshire District Councils) are looking to create a framework for hybrid mail (printing  posting of external correspondence) and general and specific printing. 
The framework will be for 4 years with a possible 2 call-offs up to 3 years making a maximum of 6 years.

The proposal is to carry out an OJEU competitive tender with negotiation for online service(s) to deliver the different functionality required - as Lots - for bulk printing and mailing, document production and specialist printing. The organisation has a desire to save 10% on annual hybrid mail costs but recognises print volumes are declining due to email and web-based correspondence.
This contract will be utilising a Lot structure as follows:
Lot 1 - General Hybrid mail - Print, insert and dispatch day to day variable data letters which could include variable or fixed data inserts
Lot 2 - Revenue & Benefits Hybrid Mail - Print, insert and dispatch council tax and benefit notifications which will include day to day bills, reminders, summonses and complete annual billing fulfilment
Lot 3 - Electoral Registration Hybrid Mail - All election printing, post and dispatch including polling day printing
Lot 4 - General Printing - Generally fixed data printing which could include larger volumes, colour magazines, letterheads, booklets and committee agendas. Additionally, a range of print finishing options including spiral/comb binding and stapling is included within this category
Lot 5 - Specialist - Could include banners and posters suitable for external use, specialist Never Tear paper and hologram printing
Lot 6 - Local / Urgent Print (HDC) - (max of 10k p.a. )
Lot 7 - Local / Urgent Print (CCC) - (max of 10k p.a)

releases/0/tender/title: Framework Agreement for the Design, Supply and Installation of Sectional Semi-Permanent Ramps
releases/0/tender/description:
This framework is for a single supplier and a reserve supplier for the Design, Supply and Installation of Sectional Semi-Permanent Ramps

Background

Project Background

Adaptations are currently delivered through Durham and Darlington Home Improvement Agency (HIA).  HIA deliver works and services across the Durham County Council and Darlington Borough Council areas. HIA also assist vulnerable homeowners and tenants, who are older, disabled or on low incomes to repair or adapt their homes.

Adaptations are available to owner-occupiers, landlords and tenants of registered providers and are delivered to people who have been assessed by an Occupational Therapist (OT) as having an essential need to enable them to live more independently.

Scope of ramps
The range of ramps delivered will include individually designed sectional semi-permanent ramps. The contractor will be expected to remove ramps that are no longer required, refurbish and store any reusable parts and reuse these parts in future ramp installations.The contract for use by DCC, additional Contracting Authorities/NFP Community Leisure Organisations, who have entered into a Procurement Service Level Agreement with DCC.  A list of SLA partners is available: http://www.durham.gov.uk/dobusinesswithus
